listing.overview: Visualize Trello cards in a calendar view.
listing.description:
Bring perspective to due dates with the Calendar Power-Up for Trello. Whether you are planning a conference, managing an editorial calendar, or organizing a family vacation, the Calendar Power-Up let’s you display cards with due dates in a weekly or monthly calendar view. Easily prioritize cards by dragging and dropping them on the calendar to automatically update their due dates, and export your Trello calendar to third party apps with an iCalendar link.

- Display and filter cards with due dates in a weekly or monthly calendar view.

- Manage due dates by dragging and dropping cards on the calendar.

- Easily see completed tasks by marking due dates complete.

- Export a board’s calendar to third party calendars with each board’s unique iCalendar link.

- The Calendar Power-Up is supported on the web and iOS and Android mobile devices.

![screenshot](https://calendar.trello.services/images/Calendar_1.jpg)

cards.name: Your schedule doesn't have to follow the current pattern of two lessons-lab-two lessons-lab daily. We are aware that some lessons take way more time than some others so limiting the lesson time to one hour shouldn't be your constraint.

You don't have to cover all the lessons and the labs that are currently on the LMS. Decide what is the core of each module from your perspective and define MPV and the lesson plan that should support an average student to successfully complete our course with good knowledge.
Continuing on the previous statement, decide which lessons and labs can be moved to the Self-Guided section.

Not all lessons need to be covered in the learning weeks (weeks: 1, 2, 4, 5, 7), some of the content can be thought during project weeks as well (weeks: 3, 6, 8, 9). Ex. deployment lessons, and maybe some other content that you don't find as necessary for MVP but could be added to power up the projects.

cards.desc:
a) this will help you in case you go over with the time for some learning unit, 
b) this will give you time to review some concepts one more time, 
c) this will give you the chance to introduce some concepts that you find important personally for the market where your campus is, but those concepts currently are not included in the curriculum, 
d) in case you don't use it daily, move forward to introducing the concepts from the following day and accumulate those un-used hours to have workshop on some concepts that are maybe more time demanding, or to work as a group on some project - ex.develop chat feature, add some creativity to the course - introduce some UX/UI concepts (wireframes, usability, colors, accessibility, ...), ...
cards.name: Plan your day for 7 hours learning + 1-hour extra time and inside read why:
If you think some of these things won't work good for you, reach out and let's talk about that and find an alternative solution.
Feel free to add some labels - to point out what is mandatory to be covered, what could be moved to self-guided lessons, what could potentially be moved to be covered during the project weeks, etc.
